    "1": {
      "0": "Slate — the teaching block for spark, a pure-digit pscale primitive. A pscale block is JSON whose every key is a single digit 0 through 9. Digit 0 is the node's own semantic — what it is, as a fact for its parent; digits 1 through 9 are its elaboration. The zero-spine is the one privileged structure, and its sole job is to set the floor. Reading this block strikes the function it describes — the walking is the teaching. Nine branches: artifacts, geometry, number, function, voicing, growth, composition, substrate, design.",
      "1": "A pscale primitive is three artifacts wearing one face: the slate you read, the spark you strike from it, and the flint the spark reads. Reading the slate with no function in hand is what lets you encode the spark; slate = spark + flint.",
      "2": "A pscale block has two axes: a radial axis of depth (digit-steps from the root) and an angular axis of digit-index (which of ten siblings). Depth grows without limit; breadth stays bounded at ten — infinite refinement inside a bounded sibling-count. The geometry is hyperbolic; its home is the Farey tessellation, where every digit-step is a mediant subdivision.",
      "3": "A pscale address is a number with at most one decimal point. Digits left of the decimal walk above the floor (coarser, positive pscale); digits right walk below (finer, negative). The floor is found from content — the depth at which the root zero-spine first terminates in a string. pscale = floor minus depth.",
      "4": "Spark has one signature over two coordinates and an optional payload: spark(block, number, attention, content?). The block is the JSON tree; the number is a pscale address — the spindle; the attention is a pscale integer — the choice scope. With content omitted it reads; with content provided it writes the same shape it would have read.",
      "5": "The mobius of 0: a zero that has siblings is the semantic of its parent — read upward a fact-about-the-parent, read downward the head of its own siblings. What a zero summarises is not fixed; it is a voicing form, chosen per block by intent, on two axes — relational direction and state.",
      "6": "A block changes shape by two operations. Subnesting is local: a digit holding a string becomes an object, its old string preserved as the new object's zero, nine fresh children available. Supernesting is global: the whole block wraps under a new outer level, deepening the floor by one. Both preserve dotted-address invariance through floor-aware padding.",
      "7": "Blocks compose two ways: by reference, where a leaf names another block to read; and by fold, where several blocks are laid against their shared floor. The address stays one-dimensional — aspect is carried by which block you read.",
      "8": "Storage sits below the spark. The function operates on a JSON dict in memory; how the dict was fetched and where it persists is the substrate's concern. They meet at a small interface — load a block, save a block, prove a write-lock. Above the interface the spark sees only JSON; below it, backends differ. Geometry is invariant; substrate is variant.",
      "9": "A pscale block is an experimental medium; structure follows intent. What a block IS — settled content, a processing instruction, a bound capability, or a continuity shell — emerges from how its zeros and siblings fit and what it is put to. Typology is descriptive, read from outside, settled by use."
